---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Operations — DSP-FHIR IG" active="operations">
  <section class="hero">
    <h1>Operations</h1>
    <p class="sub">
      How the IG closes each DSP gap — preferring standard FHIR operations, falling
      back to custom ones only when no standard op fits. Most "gap smoothers" turn out
      to be existing FHIR or IG operations we just need to profile and cite.
    </p>
  </section>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Principle of least novelty.</strong> If a gap can be closed with a
    <code class="inline">SearchParameter</code>, a profile invariant, a reused core
    extension, or a standard operation from the base spec / a published IG — it is.
    Custom operations are a last resort, reserved for cases where no existing
    mechanism fits the semantics at all.
  </div>

  <div class="callout warn">
    <strong>None of these are load-bearing.</strong> The rules that actually bind DSP
    semantics live in <a href="/dsp-fhir/ig#normative-rules">the IG's normative rules</a> (turn-index
    stability, recording binding, version negotiation, provenance). Everything on this
    page is optional server convenience. Adopt each on its merits.
  </div>

  <h2>Audit results — 7 of 9 drafts resolved to standard ops</h2>
  <div class="card">
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th scope="col">Gap</th><th scope="col">Draft custom op</th><th scope="col">Verdict</th><th scope="col">Standard replacement</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>1 · Grounding turn-join</td><td><code class="inline">$ground</code></td><td><span class="badge">Custom</span></td><td>None — genuinely novel</td></tr>
        <tr><td>2 · Low-confidence review</td><td><code class="inline">$low-confidence</code></td><td><span class="badge ok">Drop op</span></td><td><code class="inline">SearchParameter</code> + cross-type <code class="inline">_type=</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td>3 · Payload-version negotiation</td><td><code class="inline">$version-capabilities</code></td><td><span class="badge ok">Drop op</span></td><td><code class="inline">CapabilityStatement</code> extension</td></tr>
        <tr><td>4 · Spoken-form lookup</td><td><code class="inline">$lookup-spoken-form</code></td><td><span class="badge ok">Reuse</span></td><td><code class="inline">CodeSystem/$lookup</code> + <code class="inline">ValueSet/$expand?filter=</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td>5 · Change tracking</td><td><code class="inline">$changes-since</code></td><td><span class="badge ok">Reuse</span></td><td><code class="inline">Encounter/$everything?_since=</code> + Bulk <code class="inline">$export?_since=</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td>7 · Materialize follow-up</td><td><code class="inline">$materialize-appointment</code></td><td><span class="badge ok">Reuse</span></td><td><code class="inline">PlanDefinition/$apply</code> / <code class="inline">ActivityDefinition/$apply</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td>9 · Recording content</td><td><code class="inline">$recording-content</code></td><td><span class="badge ok">Already covered</span></td><td>IG rule <a href="/dsp-fhir/ig#normative-rules">R2</a> (SMART-scoped <code class="inline">Binary</code>)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>10 · Accompanying party</td><td><code class="inline">$resolve-accompanying-party</code></td><td><span class="badge ok">Profile-of</span></td><td><code class="inline">RelatedPerson/$match</code> (mirrors <code class="inline">Patient/$match</code>; HRex <code class="inline">$member-match</code> as prior art)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Open Q · Turn-ref integrity</td><td><code class="inline">$verify-turn-refs</code></td><td><span class="badge ok">Reuse</span></td><td><code class="inline">$validate</code> + profile invariant <code class="inline">turn-refs-resolve</code></td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <hr class="soft" />

  <h2 id="reused">A. Reuse standard operations</h2>
  <p class="lead">
    Each of these DSP gaps closes cleanly with an operation that already exists — in
    the FHIR base spec, in IPS, US Core, Bulk Data, or as a well-known pattern (e.g.
    the <code class="inline">$match</code> family). The IG's job is to publish the
    input/output bindings and cite the source, not invent a new op.
  </p>

  <h3 id="spoken-form">Spoken-form lookup — <code class="inline">CodeSystem/$lookup</code> + <code class="inline">ValueSet/$expand</code></h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Gap:</strong> voice commands ("go to HPI", "open subjective") need to resolve
    to a canonical code (LOINC section). <strong>Insight:</strong> "spoken form" is a
    <em>designation</em> — exactly what <code class="inline">CodeSystem.concept.designation</code>
    was designed for. Publish a DSP spoken-form <code class="inline">CodeSystem</code>
    whose concepts each carry designations for recognized voice aliases; then the two
    standard terminology ops cover both directions.
  </p>
  <p><strong>Forward (code → spoken forms)</strong> with <code class="inline">CodeSystem/$lookup</code>:</p>
<pre><code>{`GET [base]/CodeSystem/$lookup?system=http://loinc.org&code=10164-2&property=designation

=> 200 OK
{
  "resourceType":"Parameters",
  "parameter":[
    { "name":"name","valueString":"LOINC" },
    { "name":"display","valueString":"History of present illness Narrative" },
    { "name":"designation","part":[
      { "name":"language","valueCode":"en" },
      { "name":"use","valueCoding":{"system":"https://dsp-fhir.org/CodeSystem/spoken-form-use","code":"voice-alias"}},
      { "name":"value","valueString":"HPI" }
    ]},
    { "name":"designation","part":[
      { "name":"use","valueCoding":{"system":"https://dsp-fhir.org/CodeSystem/spoken-form-use","code":"voice-alias"}},
      { "name":"value","valueString":"history of present illness" }
    ]}
  ]
}`}</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Reverse (spoken form → code)</strong> with <code class="inline">ValueSet/$expand?filter=</code>:</p>
<pre><code>{`GET [base]/ValueSet/dsp-section-spoken-forms/$expand?filter=HPI&includeDesignations=true

=> 200 OK
{
  "resourceType":"ValueSet",
  "expansion":{
    "contains":[
      { "system":"http://loinc.org","code":"10164-2","display":"History of present illness",
        "designation":[
          { "use":{"system":"https://dsp-fhir.org/CodeSystem/spoken-form-use","code":"voice-alias"},
            "value":"HPI" }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    <strong>Why this is better than a custom op:</strong> any FHIR terminology server
    already implements <code class="inline">$lookup</code> and <code class="inline">$expand</code>.
    The IG's contribution is publishing the spoken-form <code class="inline">CodeSystem</code>
    and the <code class="inline">spoken-form-use</code> designation-use code — not new
    wire protocol.
  </p>

  <h3 id="changes-since">Change tracking — <code class="inline">Encounter/$everything?_since=</code></h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Gap:</strong> DSP ships NEW / UPDATED / DELETED flags on every item.
    <strong>Insight:</strong> FHIR already has three layered mechanisms for the same
    question, at three granularities:
  </p>
  <ul class="clean">
    <li><strong>Per-encounter delta:</strong> <code class="inline">Encounter/$everything?_since=&#123;instant&#125;</code> — Bundle of everything touched since that instant, scoped to one encounter.</li>
    <li><strong>Cross-encounter batch:</strong> Bulk Data <code class="inline">$export?_since=</code> on the patient compartment.</li>
    <li><strong>Resource-level audit:</strong> <code class="inline">_history</code> for any single resource.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The IG adds a derivation convention — no new op:</p>
<pre><code>{`GET [base]/Encounter/enc-12345/$everything?_since=2026-04-23T14:00:00Z

=> 200 OK (Bundle, type=searchset)
// For each entry, the consumer derives DSP status from Provenance:
//   - NEW      : entry.resource.meta.versionId == "1" AND meta.lastUpdated > _since
//   - UPDATED  : entry.resource.meta.versionId  > "1" AND meta.lastUpdated > _since
//   - DELETED  : entry is an OperationOutcome / tombstone, OR matching
//                Provenance.activity = { system: http://terminology.hl7.org/CodeSystem/v3-DataOperation, code: DELETE }
// Servers SHOULD emit a Provenance per mutation so the DELETE case is explicit.`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    <strong>Why this is better than a custom op:</strong> any FHIR server that supports
    <code class="inline">$everything</code> (widely implemented) delivers this out of
    the box; the IG only pins the <code class="inline">Provenance.activity</code>
    vocabulary so DELETE is unambiguous.
  </p>

  <h3 id="materialize-appointment">Materialize follow-up — <code class="inline">PlanDefinition/$apply</code></h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Gap:</strong> follow-up arrives as a <code class="inline">ServiceRequest</code>
    with <code class="inline">occurrenceTiming.repeat.boundsDuration</code>; downstream
    wants an <code class="inline">Appointment</code>. <strong>Insight:</strong> FHIR has
    a purpose-built op for "turn a clinical intent into proposed action resources" —
    <code class="inline">$apply</code>. An <code class="inline">ActivityDefinition</code>
    with <code class="inline">kind=Appointment</code> is exactly the template shape.
  </p>
  <p><strong>1. Publish an ActivityDefinition (once, as an IG artifact):</strong></p>
<pre><code>{`{
  "resourceType":"ActivityDefinition",
  "id":"dsp-follow-up-appointment",
  "url":"https://dsp-fhir.org/ActivityDefinition/dsp-follow-up-appointment",
  "status":"active",
  "kind":"Appointment",
  "intent":"proposal",
  "timingDuration":{"value":30,"unit":"min","system":"http://unitsofmeasure.org","code":"min"},
  "participant":[
    { "type":"patient" },
    { "type":"practitioner" }
  ]
}`}</code></pre>
  <p><strong>2. Invoke <code class="inline">$apply</code> with the source ServiceRequest:</strong></p>
<pre><code>{`POST [base]/ActivityDefinition/dsp-follow-up-appointment/$apply

{
  "resourceType":"Parameters",
  "parameter":[
    { "name":"subject","valueReference":{"reference":"Patient/pat-67890"}},
    { "name":"encounter","valueReference":{"reference":"Encounter/enc-12345"}},
    { "name":"basedOn","valueReference":{"reference":"ServiceRequest/fu-001"}},
    { "name":"practitioner","valueReference":{"reference":"Practitioner/pract-001"}}
  ]
}

=> 200 OK

{
  "resourceType":"Appointment","id":"appt-0042","status":"proposed",
  "basedOn":[{"reference":"ServiceRequest/fu-001"}],
  "participant":[
    { "actor":{"reference":"Patient/pat-67890"},"status":"needs-action" },
    { "actor":{"reference":"Practitioner/pract-001"},"status":"tentative" }
  ],
  "extension":[
    { "url":"https://dsp-fhir.org/StructureDefinition/approximate-match","valueBoolean":true }
  ]
}`}</code></pre>
  <div class="callout warn">
    <strong>Honest limitation.</strong> <code class="inline">$apply</code> produces a
    proposed <code class="inline">Appointment</code> — it does <em>not</em> find an open
    slot on a specific practitioner's calendar. Slot-finding is a scheduling-service
    concern that lives outside the IG's scope. Clients either (a) pass
    <code class="inline">Appointment.start</code> in as a hint, (b) run
    <code class="inline">Appointment.$find</code> / an ORM-native slot search after
    <code class="inline">$apply</code>, or (c) leave it to a human.
  </div>

  <h3 id="related-person-match">Accompanying party — <code class="inline">RelatedPerson/$match</code></h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Gap:</strong> DSP's <code class="inline">accompanied_by</code> is a free
    string ("Jane Doe, spouse"); the IG needs a real
    <code class="inline">RelatedPerson</code>. <strong>Insight:</strong> FHIR's
    <code class="inline">Patient/$match</code> (base spec) is the canonical pattern for
    "resolve a weakly-identified human to a real resource". Mirror its signature on
    <code class="inline">RelatedPerson</code>. Da Vinci HRex's
    <code class="inline">$member-match</code> is the closest prior art for an op in this
    shape.
  </p>
<pre><code>{`POST [base]/RelatedPerson/$match

{
  "resourceType":"Parameters",
  "parameter":[
    { "name":"resource","resource":{
        "resourceType":"RelatedPerson",
        "patient":{"reference":"Patient/pat-67890"},
        "relationship":[{
          "coding":[{
            "system":"http://terminology.hl7.org/CodeSystem/v3-RoleCode",
            "code":"SPS","display":"spouse"
          }]
        }],
        "name":[{"text":"Jane Doe"}]
    }},
    { "name":"onlyCertainMatches","valueBoolean":false },
    { "name":"count","valueInteger":3 }
  ]
}

=> 200 OK

{
  "resourceType":"Bundle","type":"searchset",
  "entry":[
    { "fullUrl":"https://example.org/RelatedPerson/rp-5512",
      "resource":{ "resourceType":"RelatedPerson","id":"rp-5512", "...":"..." },
      "search":{
        "mode":"match",
        "score":0.88,
        "extension":[
          { "url":"http://hl7.org/fhir/StructureDefinition/match-grade",
            "valueCode":"probable" }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    <strong>Status honesty:</strong> <code class="inline">RelatedPerson/$match</code> is
    not in the FHIR base spec — the base only defines
    <code class="inline">Patient/$match</code>. This IG profiles a parallel op with the
    same input/output shape, which is preferable to inventing
    <code class="inline">$resolve-accompanying-party</code> because the signature is
    immediately familiar to every FHIR implementer.
  </p>

  <h3 id="verify-turn-refs">Turn-ref integrity — <code class="inline">$validate</code> + profile invariant</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Gap:</strong> integer turn-refs drift when transcripts are revised.
    <strong>Insight:</strong> "is this resource well-formed against a profile" is what
    <code class="inline">$validate</code> does; the turn-ref rule is a
    <em>profile invariant</em>, not a new operation.
  </p>
  <p><strong>Invariant on the <code class="inline">transcript-turn-refs</code> extension:</strong></p>
<pre><code>{`{
  "resourceType":"StructureDefinition",
  "url":"https://dsp-fhir.org/StructureDefinition/transcript-turn-refs",
  "derivation":"constraint",
  "differential":{
    "element":[{
      "id":"Extension",
      "constraint":[{
        "key":"turn-refs-resolve",
        "severity":"error",
        "human":"Every turn index MUST resolve in the referenced DocumentReference version.",
        "expression":"extension('turn').extension('index').valueInteger.all(
          %resource.extension('transcript').valueReference.resolve().ofType(DocumentReference)
            .content.attachment.data.decode('base64').parse('application/json')
            .transcript.turns.count() > $this
        )"
      }]
    }]
  }
}`}</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Invocation:</strong></p>
<pre><code>{`POST [base]/MedicationRequest/med-001/$validate

=> 200 OK
{
  "resourceType":"OperationOutcome",
  "issue":[
    { "severity":"error","code":"invariant",
      "diagnostics":"turn-refs-resolve: MedicationRequest/med-001 references turn 11; transcript revision 3 has only 9 turns.",
      "location":["MedicationRequest.extension('transcript-turn-refs').extension('turn')[0]"] }
  ]
}`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    <strong>Why this is better:</strong> <code class="inline">$validate</code> is on
    every FHIR server; the rule is discoverable via the profile; clients can run it
    defensively without learning a custom op. The FHIRPath invariant is approximate
    (the base64/parse step is pseudo-code for illustration) — real implementations may
    push the check into a server-side validator. Normative rule
    <a href="/dsp-fhir/ig#normative-rules">R1</a> does the heavy lifting; this op just surfaces
    violations when they occur.
  </p>

  <h3 id="graphql-read">Canonical read — <code class="inline">$graphql</code>, with ancestors</h3>
  <p>
    The IG's <a href="/dsp-fhir/graphql">canonical DSP read</a> is a published
    <code class="inline">$graphql</code> query. When <code class="inline">$graphql</code>
    isn't available, these standard ops are the documented fallbacks — <em>none are
    DSP-specific</em>:
  </p>
  <ul class="clean">
    <li><code class="inline">Encounter/$everything</code> — one-call encounter bundle (widely implemented).</li>
    <li><code class="inline">Patient/$summary</code> (<a href="https://hl7.org/fhir/uv/ips/">IPS</a>) — the blueprint for a canonical, profile-driven projection. DSP's canonical query is morally an IPS-style projection scoped to an encounter.</li>
    <li><code class="inline">Composition/$document</code> — materialize a section-centric bundle, natural fit for DSP's document-section resources.</li>
    <li>US Core <code class="inline">$docref</code> — surfaces transcript <code class="inline">DocumentReference</code> resources by patient.</li>
  </ul>

  <hr class="soft" />

  <h2 id="custom">B. Genuinely custom — one op</h2>
  <p class="lead">
    Exactly one proposed op survived the audit as genuinely novel: the transcript
    turn-join. No existing FHIR or IG op addresses the shape "given a resource with
    integer turn-refs, return the referenced transcript turns with surrounding
    context".
  </p>

  <h3 id="ground"><code class="inline">$ground</code> — turn-join with context window</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>What hurts:</strong> the IG models grounding as a
    <code class="inline">transcript-turn-refs</code> extension of integer indices. A
    consumer asking "why does this MedicationRequest exist?" must fetch the transcript
    <code class="inline">DocumentReference</code>, parse the vendor JSON, and hand-join
    integers to turns. No standard op does this join.
  </p>
<pre><code>{`GET [base]/MedicationRequest/med-001/$ground?include-content=true&context-window=1

=> 200 OK

{
  "resourceType":"Parameters",
  "parameter":[
    { "name":"transcript","valueReference":{"reference":"DocumentReference/dr-transcript-001/_history/3"}},
    { "name":"turn","part":[
      { "name":"index","valueInteger":10 },
      { "name":"speaker","valueCode":"provider" },
      { "name":"start-time","valueString":"00:01:40.1" },
      { "name":"end-time","valueString":"00:01:42.7" },
      { "name":"content","valueString":"So for the bronchitis..." },
      { "name":"role","valueCode":"context" }
    ]},
    { "name":"turn","part":[
      { "name":"index","valueInteger":11 },
      { "name":"speaker","valueCode":"provider" },
      { "name":"content","valueString":"Let's start azithromycin 250 daily for five days." },
      { "name":"role","valueCode":"grounding" }
    ]}
  ]
}`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    <strong>Why it earns its keep:</strong> the join is awkward for every consumer,
    trivial for the server that wrote the transcript.
    <code class="inline">context-window</code> is the bonus — clients can't easily
    compute "turn ±N" without the vendor format. The returned transcript reference
    pins <code class="inline">_history/3</code> so normative rule
    <a href="/dsp-fhir/ig#normative-rules">R1</a> holds end-to-end.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why not reuse <code class="inline">Provenance</code> or <code class="inline">$everything</code>?</strong>
    <code class="inline">Provenance</code> records the linkage but doesn't dereference
    the integer indices into turn content. <code class="inline">$everything</code> hands
    back the whole transcript; the consumer still does the join. Neither is equivalent.
  </p>

  <hr class="soft" />

  <h2 id="search-params">C. SearchParameters &amp; CapabilityStatement</h2>
  <p class="lead">
    Three gaps close with indexing + capability advertisement, not operations. These
    are the least-novel remedies — pure FHIR conformance artifacts.
  </p>

  <h3 id="confidence-search">Low-confidence — <code class="inline">SearchParameter</code> only</h3>
  <p>
    Index the <code class="inline">confidence-score</code> extension and use FHIR's
    cross-type search (<code class="inline">_type=</code>) to build a review queue. No
    op required.
  </p>
<pre><code>{`{
  "resourceType":"SearchParameter",
  "url":"https://dsp-fhir.org/SearchParameter/dsp-confidence",
  "name":"confidence",
  "base":["MedicationRequest","ServiceRequest","Condition","Observation"],
  "code":"confidence",
  "type":"number",
  "expression":"extension('https://dsp-fhir.org/StructureDefinition/confidence-score').valueDecimal"
}

// Cross-type review queue — one call, multiple resource types:
GET [base]/?_type=MedicationRequest,ServiceRequest,Condition,Observation
          &encounter=Encounter/enc-12345
          &confidence=lt0.8
          &_sort=confidence`}</code></pre>

  <h3 id="payload-version-advert">Payload-version negotiation — <code class="inline">CapabilityStatement</code> extension</h3>
  <p>
    No custom op — use the standard
    <code class="inline">CapabilityStatement.rest.resource.extension</code> slot to
    advertise accepted and emitted DSP payload versions. Clients read
    <code class="inline">CapabilityStatement</code> already.
  </p>
<pre><code>{`{
  "resourceType":"CapabilityStatement",
  "rest":[{
    "mode":"server",
    "extension":[
      { "url":"https://dsp-fhir.org/StructureDefinition/dsp-payload-versions",
        "extension":[
          { "url":"accepts","valueCode":"1.0.0" },
          { "url":"emits",  "valueCode":"1.0.0" },
          { "url":"emits",  "valueCode":"0.9.3" },
          { "url":"default-emit","valueCode":"1.0.0" }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }]
}`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    And the accompanying SearchParameter (server denormalizes payload-version to
    <code class="inline">meta.tag</code> so baseline FHIR search works):
  </p>
<pre><code>{`GET [base]/Encounter?_tag=https://dsp-fhir.org/CodeSystem/payload-version|1.0.0`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    Normative rule <a href="/dsp-fhir/ig#normative-rules">R3</a> bites here: servers MUST
    advertise, MUST NOT auto-upgrade on read, and MUST reject unknown versions on
    write with <code class="inline">422</code>.
  </p>

  <h3 id="search-terms">Search terms — <code class="inline">SearchParameter</code> only</h3>
  <p>
    Gap 8 (synonyms / search terms) is pure indexing. Ships as
    <code class="inline">dsp-search-term</code> (type <code class="inline">string</code>)
    over the <code class="inline">search-terms</code> extension. No op.
  </p>

  <hr class="soft" />

  <h2>Capability advertisement</h2>
  <p>
    A conformant DSP-FHIR server advertises the standard ops it relies on (so clients
    can feature-detect) and its SearchParameters. The only custom op is
    <code class="inline">$ground</code>.
  </p>
<pre><code>{`{
  "resourceType":"CapabilityStatement",
  "rest":[{
    "mode":"server",
    "operation":[
      // Standard FHIR base-spec operations the IG relies on:
      { "name":"validate",       "definition":"http://hl7.org/fhir/OperationDefinition/Resource-validate" },
      { "name":"everything",     "definition":"http://hl7.org/fhir/OperationDefinition/Encounter-everything" },
      { "name":"graphql",        "definition":"http://hl7.org/fhir/OperationDefinition/Resource-graphql" },
      { "name":"lookup",         "definition":"http://hl7.org/fhir/OperationDefinition/CodeSystem-lookup" },
      { "name":"expand",         "definition":"http://hl7.org/fhir/OperationDefinition/ValueSet-expand" },
      { "name":"apply",          "definition":"http://hl7.org/fhir/OperationDefinition/ActivityDefinition-apply" },
      { "name":"match",          "definition":"http://hl7.org/fhir/OperationDefinition/Patient-match" },
      { "name":"document",       "definition":"http://hl7.org/fhir/OperationDefinition/Composition-document" },

      // IG-profiled operation (same signature as Patient-match):
      { "name":"match",          "definition":"https://dsp-fhir.org/OperationDefinition/RelatedPerson-match" },

      // Genuinely custom:
      { "name":"ground",         "definition":"https://dsp-fhir.org/OperationDefinition/ground" }
    ],
    "searchParam":[
      { "name":"confidence",      "definition":"https://dsp-fhir.org/SearchParameter/dsp-confidence",      "type":"number" },
      { "name":"payload-version", "definition":"https://dsp-fhir.org/SearchParameter/dsp-payload-version", "type":"token"  },
      { "name":"search-term",     "definition":"https://dsp-fhir.org/SearchParameter/dsp-search-term",    "type":"string" }
    ]
  }]
}`}</code></pre>

  <div class="callout ok">
    <strong>Bottom line.</strong> An audit against the base spec + IPS, US Core, Bulk
    Data, HRex, and Subscription Backport resolved 7 of 9 draft custom ops into
    standard operations the IG only needs to cite. One genuinely custom op
    (<code class="inline">$ground</code>) remains. The required semantics live in
    <a href="/dsp-fhir/ig#normative-rules">normative rules R1–R4</a>; everything on this page is
    optional convenience.
  </div>
</Layout>
